Three Bulls had grazed and fought together for so long that no Lion dared trouble them.

At dusk on a flat plain, the silhouettes of 3 bulls stood widely scattered, each carrying the same well-known strength 2. Roar the lion, of strength 15, watched the long shadows lean across the grass untroubled by what others thought. The lion could meet any one of those silhouettes alone; the herd's combined strength of 6, however, would simply trample him. The bulls themselves shifted in a panic at every distant snap of grass. All that remained was the boolean: did the lion truly need them divided to win?

