A young farmhand at the village liked to come round at sunrise just to watch Fiona collect from the goose. The bird would settle, ruffle, and stand, leaving 1 golden egg in the straw — never more, never fewer. Fiona would gather them grateful for every bite, smiling at the boy, and tuck them into a folded cloth. She kept up the routine for 12 days, and at the end the boy asked, eyes wide, just how many golden eggs the goose had given altogether.

