In the heart of an open meadow stood 5 bulls, each tested at the spring tournament to be of strength 9. Mane the lion watched from the long grass untroubled by what others thought, her own measured strength known to be 14. Bull by bull, she could outmatch any one of them one-on-one. But when the bulls had stood shoulder to shoulder, their unified strength came to 45 — too great for any single lion. The question now was simply whether the lion's only winning path lay through dividing the herd.

