Greed and patience, as everyone knows, do not sit at the same table — and a golden-egg goose tests them both.

More than once Charlie had heard a sly voice whisper that the goose was wasted on slow daily laying. But he swallowed the thought each time, fed the bird, and let the gold come at its own pace. The goose laid 1 golden egg a day, and at the market each egg fetched 41 coins. By the time the small chest of coins beside the hearth held 369 coins in all, he sat by the hearth, grateful for every bite, and looked at the worn ledger where every egg, every coin, every trip to the market had been written down in a careful hand.

Question: for how many days the goose had been laying?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Daily revenue is per-day eggs × per-egg coins; days = total-coins / coins-per-day.

