Pride goes before a fall, especially when a Milkmaid begins to plan her wealth too eagerly.

Nan walked the long road to market with her wooden pail balanced upon her head, the milk inside slopping gently with every step. Imagining all that he might gain, she began to count out her coming fortune. The milk would buy 10 eggs from the poultry stall; each would hatch into a fine hen; each hen would lay 167 eggs in the course of a year; and every one of those eggs would fetch 1 coin at market. She walked faster, smiling to herself.

