In the valley grassland, Mane the lion crouched at the reed-line untroubled by what others thought, watching 3 bulls drink at separate bends of the slow stream. Each bull had strength 9; the lion's own strength was 14. Solo, no bull at the water could withstand her; together at the bend they had once held 27 between them, more than enough to chase a lion off. The math of the situation was clear, and the only thing left to settle was the boolean: did the lion's chance depend on keeping the bulls divided?

