A hungry Fox came upon a vine of grapes hanging just out of reach.

Along the white stone wall that ringed an old vineyard, a fig tree had grown over the top and dropped its fruit on the wrong side. The lowest dark fig hung 12 feet above the dusty lane where Vix the fox now stood, his heart sinking that the climb up the slope had cost her so much breath for so little gain. She sprang once to test herself: the bound carried her 3 feet aloft. She settled to count how many such efforts, each lifting 3 feet, would suffice.

