The afternoon was hot enough to crack a leaf, and Caw, near to giving up the search for water, settled at the rim of an old jar that someone had left in the sun. The water at the bottom — only 5 centimeters deep — shimmered just out of reach. A pile of dry beads sat nearby. One by one she ferried them up and let them fall, 11 beads altogether, each one shouldering the surface up by another 3 centimeters.

